# ── Compiled binaries and build outputs ──────────────────────────────────────
# The bin/ directory is the conventional output location for compiled binaries.
# Binaries are platform-specific and must never be committed; they are
# reproduced deterministically from source via `make build`.
bin/
*.exe
*.exe~
*.dll
*.so
*.dylib

# ── Test artefacts ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
*.test
*.out
coverage.html
coverage.out

# ── Dependency directories ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The module cache is managed by `go mod download` and must not be committed.
# Committing vendor/ is a valid alternative for air-gapped CI environments
# but adds significant noise to pull request diffs; prefer go.sum for
# reproducibility.
vendor/

# ── Environment files and secrets ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# .env files contain real credentials and must never reach version control.
# .env.example documents the required variables with safe placeholder values
# and is the only env file that should be committed.
.env
.env.*
!.env.example

# ── IDE and editor directories ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# IDE configuration is machine-specific. Committing it forces every team
# member to use the same editor settings and pollutes the repository with
# files that have no bearing on the application's behaviour.
.idea/
.vscode/
*.swp
*.swo

# ── Operating system artefacts ────────────────────────────────────────────────
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# ── Go workspace files ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# go.work is used for local multi-module development and is inherently
# machine-specific. It must not be committed to the shared repository.
go.work
go.work.sum
